These proofs are simple because the definitions align such that the real part of the restricted function is exactly the real function defined in the theorem statement. The complex value on the imaginary axis is purely real, so its real part is the value itself, and its imaginary part is 0. The coercion `â†‘` captures this by creating a complex number with the real part as the given real number and an imaginary part of 0.
